        </section>
        <p data-uuid="e9fbcbdffe78478f8555d783506d1f39">Within moments, the eighth floor was ablaze. The fire spread quickly to two other floors. With the doors locked, escape was nearly impossible. The building’s only fire escape collapsed under the weight of panic-stricken workers, sending them tumbling to their deaths. With flames at their backs, dozens of other workers leaped from the windows. </p>
        <p data-uuid="77036ebb83494cfe964bad9fccd4452a"> By the time firefighters brought the fire under control, 146 workers had died. At a memorial service for the victims, union leader Rose Schneiderman called for action. “It is up to the working people to save themselves,” she said. The <b><dfn title="Triangle Shirtwaist Fire">Triangle Shirtwaist Fire</dfn></b> and similar accidents led to the passage of laws improving factory safety standards.</p>
